'''Museum of Death''' is a [[museum]] with locations on [[Hollywood Boulevard]] in [[Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]], and [[New Orleans]].<ref name="roadside">{{cite web | title = Museum of Death | publisher = Roadside America | url = http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/19590 | accessdate = December 27, 2014}}</ref> It was established in June 1995 by J. D. Healy and Catherine Shultz with the museum's stated goal being "to make people happy to be alive".<ref name="heads">{{cite news | last = Gumbel | first = Andrew | title = American Times: Hollywood, California, The Doyenne of Death Heads for Tinseltown | newspaper = The Independent | location = London, UK | pages = 15 | date = December 8, 1999}}</ref>

==History==
The museum was originally established in 1995 in [[San Diego]],<ref>{{citation|newspaper=[[Daily Trojan]]|title=Museum of Death pays tribute to more than the dead|date=February 12, 2012|first=Eva|last=Recinos|url=http://dailytrojan.com/2012/02/12/museum-of-death-pays-tribute-to-more-than-the-dead/}}</ref> in a building the owners claimed was the city's first [[mortuary]]. It began as a hobby of the founders J. D. Healy and Catherine Shultz. They would write to [[serial killer]]s they were interested in, and then show off the artwork their [[pen pals]] had created once a year at a specialist show. In 1995, after a few years of exhibitions, the collection, and many other materials, were made into a museum.<ref>{{cite news | last = Canto | first = Minerva | title = Museum of Death moving to Hollywood | newspaper = The Associated Press State & Local Wire | date = November 1, 1999}}</ref>

In late 1999, the couple attempted to acquire a large amount of materials from the [[Heaven's Gate (religious group)|Heaven's Gate]] cult suicides. Although they had been able to purchase many items prior to the main police auction, their interest in buying enough merchandise to recreate the scene in its entirety, led to enormous press interest and publicity. They were subsequently evicted by their landlord, and moved to Hollywood Boulevard in Los Angeles.<ref name="heads"/>

Prior to the new Los Angeles building becoming a museum, the building was the home of [[Westbeach Recorders]], and prior to that, Producers Studio,<ref name="roadside"/><ref>{{citation|url=http://boulevardrecording.com/about/|title=About us|publisher=Boulevard Recording|accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> where [[Pink Floyd]] and others recorded.<ref>{{citation|title=Dark destinations: The Museum of Death | work=thecabinet.com | date=June 7, 2009 | url=http://www.thecabinet.com/darkdestinations/location.php?sub_id=dark_destinations&letter=m&location_id=the_museum_of_death}}</ref> The walls include deadening agents to help with recordings, which now serve to lend a quiet acoustic setting for the various exhibitions.<ref name="roadside"/>

===New Orleans branch===
{{Infobox museum
| name                = Musee de Mort Orleans
| coordinates         = {{coord|29.9560|-90.0698|type:landmark|display=inline}}
| established         = {{Start date|2014}}
| location            = 227 Dauphine St.<br>[[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]
| founder             = 
}}
{{as of|2014}}, the couple had opened up a new branch of the museum in [[New Orleans]] called "Musee de Mort Orleans".<ref name="New Orleans">{{cite news | last = Rylah | first = Juliet Bennett | title = The Museum Of Death In Hollywood Bought Dr. Kevorkian's Suicide Machine | newspaper = LAist | date = July 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{citation|work=[[Artnet News]]|title=Museum of Death Buys Dr. Kevorkian's Suicide Device | author=Sarah Cascone | date=July 22, 2014 | url=http://news.artnet.com/in-brief/museum-of-death-buys-dr-kevorkians-suicide-device-65147}}</ref> The new museum branch will have around 12,000 square metres of space, which will allow more of the collection to be displayed. The limited space at the California museum means that only a third of the items available can be shown at one time.<ref>{{cite web | last = Boehm | first = Mike | title = Museum of Death in L.A. buys Kevorkian suicide device Thanatron | date = July 21, 2014 | url = http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-jack-kevorkian-museum-of-death-hollywood-thanatron-20140718-story.html | accessdate = December 28, 2014}}</ref>

==Collection==
[[File:Head of Henri Landru.jpg|thumb|left|Severed head presented as [[Henri Désiré Landru|Henri Landru]]'s.]]
The museum displays a wide variety of art and artifacts surrounding the subject of death. Baby coffins are in one section, letters and artwork from various serial killers in another. There are films regarding [[autopsies]] as well as graphic photographs of crime victims. There is also a room filled exclusively with [[taxidermy]] of various types of animals. The museum's recreation of the [[Heaven's Gate (religious group)|Heaven's Gate]] [[mass suicide]] includes the original beds.<ref>{{cite news | last = Fox | first = Ben | title = Bidders snap up household items from site of worst mass suicide | newspaper = The Associated Press State & Local Wire | date = November 22, 1999}}</ref> However, the most notable item at the museum is the head of [[Henri Désiré Landru|Henri Landru]].<ref name="roadside"/> In 2014 the museum also acquired Thanatron, one of the original [[Euthanasia device|suicide machines]] built by [[Jack Kevorkian]].<ref name="New Orleans"/>

Once a year, the museum holds a [[Black Dahlia]] [[look-alike]] competition, where contestants have to dress as both pre and post-mortem Dahlia.<ref>{{cite news | last = Renzetti | first = Elizabeth | title = Ghost town; Hollywood, more than any other place on; earth, is death-obsessed. ELIZABETH RENZETTI; takes us on a ghoulish tour of Tinsel Town | newspaper = The Globe and Mail | location = Canada | pages = T1 | date = October 25, 2000}}</ref>

A 2001 attempt to procure a real electric chair was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news | title = Electric chair could end up in museum | newspaper = The Associated Press State & Local Wire | date = August 20, 2001}}</ref>

